      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "China's claims in the South China Sea are widely seen as overreaching and lacking a solid legal basis under international law, particularly the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS). The nine-dash line China uses to justify its claims overlaps with the Exclusive Economic Zones (EEZs) of several Southeast Asian nations, which is a major point of contention. The U.S. and other countries argue that China's actions, including the construction of artificial islands and militarization, violate the rights of other nations and threaten regional stability. This is a clear case of China asserting its dominance and disregarding international norms, which is why it's seen as aggressive and problematic by many in the international community.",
